        "introduction": [
            {
                "titre": "I need a small but super-strong magnet.",
                "sous_items": []
            },
            {
                "titre": "We have a magnetic knife rack, typically using a few small neodymium magnets to enhance magnetism. However, when adding more knives, conventional magnets may not provide enough strength to support their weight. This guide comes to the rescue, demonstrating a small experiment to create a reinforced powerful magnet.",
                "sous_items": []
            },
            {
                "titre": "I took 5 cubes (2mm x 2mm x 2mm) of neodymium magnets and arranged them in various configurations to visually experience the magnetic force of the Halbach array.",
                "sous_items": []
            },
            {
                "titre": "In method one, all the north poles are aligned to the left. (Note: The arrows in the diagram point to the north pole of the magnets.)",
                "sous_items": []
            },
            {
                "titre": "Method two displays the specific arrangement of magnetic poles known as the Halbach array. The Halbach array provides a significantly stronger magnetic field on one side and a much weaker field on the other, arranged as north right, north up, north left, north down, north right.",
                "sous_items": []
            },
            {
                "titre": "In method three, two different arrangements of the Halbach array are compared to test if their performances differ. The magnets are arranged in a pattern with alternating north pole directions; north left, north up, north right, north down, north left.",
                "sous_items": []
            },
            {
                "titre": "In method four, the magnets are arranged in a pattern with alternating north pole directions; north up, north down, north up, and so on.",
                "sous_items": []
            },
            {
                "titre": "I found a couple of websites that describe the Halbach array, such as Wikipedia and TOPMAG (TOPMAG is the source of the charts. They are an excellent resource for any magnet you can imagine!).",
                "sous_items": []
            },
            {
                "titre": "PS If you find the guide I've posted interesting, please click the 'Follow' button above. Thank you!",
                "sous_items": []
            },
            {
                "titre": "",
                "sous_items": [
                    "There are many ways to achieve this, but I will discuss four:Aligning the poles - Stacking the magnets side by side with all the north poles pointing in the same direction.",
                    "Creating a Halbach array - Halbach array is a specific magnet arrangement that results in one side of the array having a very strong magnetic field, while the other side has a much weaker field, arranged as north right, north up, north left, north down, north right.",
                    "Creating an inverse Halbach array - Similar to method three but with opposite pole directions, arranged as north left, north up, north right, north down, north left.",
                    "Alternating poles - Stacking the magnets side by side with alternating pole directions; north up, north down, north up, and so on."
                ]
            }
        ],
